{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_groomcreek_ver04/data/sn96060774/00414218258/1930111101/0134.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nBogales International\nDevoted to the Interest* ot Nogales and Vicinity\nPUBLISHED EVERY TUESDAY AND FRIDAY MORNING\nAt 225 Grand Av% Nogales, Arizona\nCRAIG POTTINGER Owner and Publisher\nRALPH RAWSTHORNE Business Manager\nAL KIRK Managing Editor\nSubscription Rate s4.ou A Year 52.50 Six Months, 45 cents a\nMonth.\nINTERNATIONAL PLATFORM\nBetter Drainage To Make Floods Impossible More Conventions\nMore Tourists\nA Law To Prohibit Jaywalking A Greater Nogales\nA Motorcycle Road Patrol To Regulate Traffic On the Nogales-\nTucson Road Development Os Mining And Agricultural Re\nsources Os This District.\nEntered as second class matter February 3, 1928 at the\npostoffice at Nogales, Arizona, under the Act of March 3. 1\u2019279.\nThe Armistice Os 1918\nTwelve years ago on November 11 the greatest\nwar of history came to an end through an armistice\nbetween the Allied powers and the United States\non the one hand and Germany on the other.\nThis historic document was signed in Marshal\nFoch\u2019s special train at Rethondes, France, at 5 o\u2019clock\na. m., and provided for the cessation of hostilities six\nhours later. Accordingly the fighting ceased at 11 a.\nm.\nWhile the Arimistice of November 11 marked the\nreal termination of the war, it was the fourth of a ser\nies of rapidly moving events which brought the ti\ntanic struggle to a close.\nBulgaria had already surrendered unconditional\nly at Salonica on September 29; Turkey had surrend\nered at Mudros on October 31, and Austria-Hungary\nhad surrendered at the headquarters of General Diaz,\nthe Italian commander, on November 3. Left thus a-j\nlone in the struggle, the defeat of Germany was in-\nevitable. j\nIn fact, Germany had appealed to President Wil\nson for peace on October 6, and the time between that\ndate and the Armistice was taken up with diplomatic\ncorrespondence and the working out of the conditions\nsubmitted to Germany for acceptance.\nThese conditions left Germany absolutely shorn\nof all military and naval power which might enable\nher to take the offensive again. Signing of the treaty\nof peace followed on June 28,1919, at Versailles, near\nParis.\nSince that time many additional treaties, pacts\nand agreements have been entered into by various na-\ntions.\nContinued efforts to insure peace are being made\nby the world\u2019s leading statesmen, and upon the re\nsults of these efforts depend the most momentous con\nsequences to the human race.\n\u2014O\u2014O\u2014O\u2014\nTwo Successful Campaigns\nThe value of united effort was clearly demontra\nted by the merchants of Nogales who unanimously\nand enthusiastically joined in the two important civ\nic movements test week, the \u201cPay-Up\u201d campaign and\nthe Merchants\u2019 Display Night.\nFor the first time in many years all of the mer\nchants in the entire city responded 100 per cent and\nthe results were most gratifying. Collections were\nreported much better during \"the week as the result\nof the splendid efforts of the chamber of commerce\ncommittee headed by Dave Levy and it is expected\nthe people of Nogales will make an effort to keep up\ntheir payments more promptly in the future.\nAs for the Merchants\u2019 Display Friday night it\nproved one of the greatest events in business revival\never before attempted in Nogales. Much credit for\nthe success of this event is due the other chamber of\ncommerce committee headed by E. S. Edmonson.\nThese two movements inaugurated and directed\nby the chamber of commerce were of untold benefit\nto Nogales and the effects will be felt for a long time\nto come.\nNeither of these campaigns, of course, couid have\nbeen successful without the cooperation of the public\nand the response on the part of the people of the cities\non both sides of the line showed clearly their confi\ndence in the merchants of Nogales and their deep per\nsonal interest in the efforts put forth by the merch\nants to improve business conditions.\nThe quality and great variety of the merchandise\nshown and the artistic manner in which it was dis\nplayed would have done credit to a city many times\nthe size of Nogales.\nFrom every standpoint these two worthy cam\npaigns were a pronounced success.\n\u2014O\u2014O\u2014O\u2014\nIndustry Spreads Out\nInstead of further concentrating in the larger\ncities, the present tendency of industrial plants is to\nward the smaller towns, according to a recent maga\nzine writer, who considers this one of the most far\nreaching movements of recent years.\nSome of the reasons for this decentralization of\nindustry are given, among them being the bringing of\nfactories closer to the raw materials and the ultimate\nconsumer, thus reducing transportation charges; the\nextension of cheap electric service to the smaller ci\nties and towns; lower living costs and better sur\nroundings for employees, and in many cases a more!\nintelligent and more dependable labor supply.\nSumming up the results which this movement\nJust the Boost That Is Needed\nwill bring about, the writer says that from now on\nwe may expect to see a marked movement toward\nthese smaller cities and towns, instead of having vast\npopulations necessary for large production herded\ntogether in a few big cities.\nThis trend of industry affords the small town\njits opportunity to share in the benefits of industrial\npayrolls. Besides, the industrial workers create a bet\nter market for farm produce. Thus industry and agri\nculture may go hand in hand in the upbuilding of\nthose communities which take advantage of their op\nportunities in this direction.\n_o_ o-o\nEnough Turkey For Everybody\nNo American housewife will have difficulty pro\ncuring a turkey to grace the Thanksgiving or Christ- j\nmas table this year, according to official advices from\nthe Department of Agriculture. For this we can give\nthanks to the drought which created exceptionally\nfavorable conditions for raising young turkeys and,\ntherefore, partially offset the decrease in hatchings\nthat resulted from low prices last year. Although the\n1930 supply is three percent less than in 1929, it is\nstill greater than in 1928 or 1927.\nCommercially raised turkeys destined for mar\nket are graded by the Department of Agriculture at\nabout 60 principal shipping points, largely in Texas!\nand the Pacific northwest. Four different grades are\nrecognized; U. S. prime, U. S. choice, U. S. medium\nand U. S. common. The Department recently had on\nhand enough labels to take care of 435 carloads of the\nfestive birds. j\n\u2014o\u2014o\u2014o\nMarrying a girl who is beautiful but dumb would\nbe ail right if she would not stay that way. I\nAfter we teach people respect for laws we\nmay hope to persuade them to have respect for in\nlaws.\nA Georgia woman declares four robbers have\nbeen into her refrigerator lately, not counting the\nice man. j\n-o\u2014o\u2014o\u2014\nCongressman declares that the time is ripe fori\na settlement of the Muscle Shoals question. Not only!\nripe, but rotten.\nA Minnesota professor made himself solid with\nthe younger generation by declaring that home work\nis bad for children.\nMussolini says he reviews his mistakes of the\nday every night before retiring. If some of us did\nthat we would lose a lot of sleejx\nIt is hinted that the crime commission will soon\nmake an exhaustive report. It will no doubt be ex-!\nhausting to those who are obliged to read it.\nNOGALES TOMBSTONE STAGES\nTime Table, Effective November 1, 1930\n(Departure--Read Down) (Arrival\u2014Read Up)\nMis Daily Daily Daily Daily Mis\nEx. Sun. Ex. Sun.\n0 7:30 AM 4:00 PM Lv Nogales Ar 3:30 PM 7:50 PM 126\n22 8:30 AM 5:00 PM Ar Patagonia Lv 2:35 PM 6:50 PM\n9:00 AM 5:05 PM Lv Patagonia Ar 2:25 PM 6:45 PM 104\n35 9:30 AM 5:30 PM Ar Sonoita Lv 2:05 PM 6:21 PM\n9:45 AM 5:35 PM Lv Sonoita Ar 1:55 PM 6:20 PM 91\n10:10 AM Ar Elgin Lv 1:35 PM\n10:20 AM Lv Elgin Ar 1:25 PM\n66 11:00 AM 6:15 PM Ar Fairbanks Lv 12:20 PM 5:35 PM\n11:10 AM 6:16 PM Lv Fairbank Ar 12:05 FM 5:30 PM 60\n75 11:30 AM 6:45 PM Ar Tombstone Lv 11:45 AM 5:15 PM\n12:01 PM Lv Tombstone Ar 5:05 PM 51\n102 1:15 PM Ar Bisbee Lv 4:00 PM\n1:25 PM Lv Bisbee Ar 3;43 pm 24\n103 1:30 PM Lv Lowell Lv 3:35 pm 23\n123 2:15 PM Ar Douglas Lv 2:45 PM C\n7:30 A. M. Stage from Nogales makes direct connections with\nGolden State at Fairbank for the East.\n4:00 P. M. Stage from Nogales makes direct connections at\nTombstone for the East.\nNOGALES INTERNATIONAL\nBy Albert T. Reid\nNewspaper To Move\nShortly To Tucson\nPamposa and Bernardo Salazar,\nowners of \u201cEl Imparcial\u2019\u2019, daily\nSpanish newspaper on Morley ave\nnue, will begin dismantling their\nplant this week preparatory to mov\ning to Tucson where they will con\ntinue publication of their daily.\nI \u201cEl Imparcial\" was founded a\nyear ago last summer, shortly after\nthe collapse of the Mexican revolu\ntion. During the revolution Barn\nardo Salazar was collector of cus\ntoms of all rebel ports and Pamposa\ncollector at Nogales, Sonora,\nj The Monteverde Printing Com\npany, which also started up in No\ngales following the revolution, is to\nmove back shortly to its former lo\ncation, Hermosillo.\ni Theron Richardson of the First\nNational Bank has returned from\nTucson where he attended the an\nnual convention of the State Bank\ners Association.\ni\n\\nEAFtIT\n1 \\test it\nj the amazing new\no/Hfsge&tic\nPERFECTED\nSCREEN GRID\n\u25a0SUPERHETERODYNE\nIsi 1950 P\nONLY JL j\ncomplete with tubes\nfree Trial\nEASIEST PAYMENTS\nGUARANTEED SER VICE\n\nI j\nG, A, Larriva 1\nDEALER\nLocated at American Urns\nStore Morley Ave. I\nPhone 18\nNOGALES, ARIZ., TUESDAY, NOV. 11, 1930\nI WOOD, COAL and KINDLING\nPrompt Delivery Service\nARIZONA WOOD COAL CO.\nPnone 354 1058 Grand Ave.\nI SPECIAL\nUntil The End Os This Month\nI 3-PIECE\nLIVING ROOM SUITE\n$94.75\nCome and See It!\niO. B. MARSH, INC.\nGrand Ave.\n\u2014m,